  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "The plateau is not a peak — it's a **collapse of dimensionality**. The system has optimized within a narrow solution space (likely: fixed morphology, uniform world, fixed growth). Evolution cannot climb because there is nowhere new to climb. Breaking the plateau requires introducing *new dimensions of trade-off*, not just finer tuning within existing ones. The three proposals restore orthogonal degrees of freedom: morphological differentiation, spatial heterogeneity, and temporal/plastic body adaptation. Beauty will re-emerge once organisms must balance multiple incompatible demands again.; [medium] Introduce heterogeneous cell differentiation with emergent specialization — allow cells to declare type (sensory, motor, structural, metabolic) with type-specific capabilities and trade-offs. Cell type determines action space and energy cost, forcing organisms to develop multi-tissue morphologies instead of homogeneous blobs. — Current optimization likely converged on a single body morphology that saturated given cell types. Introducing specialized cells creates a new morphological dimensionality. Evolution must now discover what tissue arrangements create viable strategies. Beauty can emerge from functional integration (e.g., symmetric sensory layout vs asymmetric predator-prey chase geometries). This resets the local maximum.; [easy] Implement environmental patchiness with spatially-variable physics — create distinct zones with different gravity, viscosity, food distribution, or light levels. Organisms born in one zone must either specialize or maintain costly generalist plasticity. — Uniform world fitness landscapes collapse into single peak. Patchy environment forces speciation pressure and prevents global convergence. An organism optimized for zone A fails in zone B; evolution must now balance exploration-exploitation across niches. Beauty emerges from local adaptation (color patterns matching terrain, body shape matching locomotion demands in different viscosities).; [hard] Decouple decision function from morphology — allow organism's neural/logic structure to evolve independently from body plan. Introduce a 'growth phase' where an organism's body can reorganize/remodel based on environmental signals, not just fixed ontogeny. — Plateau suggests decision optimization saturated. Allowing body plan to co-evolve with behavior unlocks new strategy space: an organism can adapt its morphology to match learned environment patterns. Current system likely has fixed morphology → frozen decision problem. Growth plasticity means the problem landscape changes with each generation, preventing convergence.",
  "evidence": [
    "trigger:plateau",
